    "client_understanding_narrative": "Michael (36) and Emily (34) are an Austin-based couple with a one-year-old son, Noah. Michael is the primary earner ($188k base + bonus) in a stable operations role, while Emily works part-time ($48k) to balance childcare. Their gross household income is approximately $242k/year, supporting annual spending of roughly $146k. Their balance sheet consists of $78k in cash, $275k in a taxable brokerage account invested entirely in US equities, and $322k in Michael's 401(k) invested entirely in US Treasuries. They carry a $472k mortgage at 3.375%. Their primary financial objectives are to fund Noah's college education starting in 2040 and to retire at age 62 with their current lifestyle maintained.",
    "client_understanding_summary": "High-earning household with a polarized asset allocation (100% equity vs. 100% treasury) and tight discretionary cash flow. While they have a strong savings foundation, their conservative retirement allocation jeopardizes their age-62 retirement goal.",
    "identified_needs": [
      "Asset allocation optimization to reduce cash drag in 401(k)",
      "Liquidity management to reduce reliance on bonus for savings",
      "Education funding strategy for Noah",
      "Survivor income protection for primary earner"
    ],
    "gaps_by_category": {
      "investment related": [
        {
          "gap": "Inefficient Portfolio Allocation",
          "discussion": "The portfolio exhibits a severe 'barbell' inefficiency: the taxable account is 100% US Equity (high volatility/tax drag), while the 401(k)\u2014the largest asset\u2014is 100% US Treasuries (low real return). This conservative positioning in the retirement account is the primary driver of the 96% failure rate in Monte Carlo simulations, as the portfolio cannot outpace inflation sufficiently to support a 30-year retirement starting at age 62."
        }
      ],
      "insurance related": [
        {
          "gap": "Primary Earner Dependency",
          "discussion": "Michael generates approximately 80% of the household income. With a $472k mortgage and a young dependent, the family's financial security is highly sensitive to his ability to earn. While they have 6 months of cash reserves, there is no confirmed life or disability coverage to bridge the gap between Emily's part-time income ($48k) and their $146k annual expense load in the event of a health shock."
        }
      ],
      "spending related": [
        {
          "gap": "Tight Structural Free Cash Flow",
          "discussion": "Despite a high gross income ($242k), the family's fixed monthly burn rate of ~$12,200 consumes nearly all of their guaranteed net monthly take-home pay ($12,300\u2013$13,100). This leaves a surplus of less than $1,000/month for new goals like college funding, making their accumulation strategy heavily dependent on Michael's variable annual bonus ($15k\u2013$22k), which is not guaranteed."
        }
      ],
      "liability related": "None"
